* 1.9 – Given a scenario, use features and tools of the Mac OS and Linux client/desktop operating systems.

** Best practices

*** Scheduled backups
- Should be routine and scheduled
*** Scheduled disk maintenance
- In macOS, through Disk Utility App
  - Permissions can be verified
  - These can become corrupted over long use
*** System updates/App Store
 - In Linux done on command line
   - Ubuntu: ~sudo apt-get update~
   - Red Hat / CentOS: ~yum update~
   - Linux desktops have GUI apps for this
*** Patch management
- macOS - done through App Store
- Linux - through above update system
*** Driver/firmware updates
- as in last slide
*** Antivirus/Anti-malware updates
- Although macOS and Linux tend to have fewer security problems, people do sometimes install antivirus / antimalware

** Tools

*** Backup/Time Machine
- macOS utility for regular backups

** Features

*** Multiple desktops/Mission Control
*** Key Chain
- password management
*** Spot Light
- maintains directory of apps
*** iCloud
- Apple's cloud storage
*** Gestures
- Cool things you can do on your trackpad
- Configured in System PReferences / Trackpad
*** Finder
- macOS version of Windows File Explorer
*** Dock
- Bar with application shortcuts, usually on the bottom
  - But can be moved
*** Boot Camp
- Allows the boot of different operating systems

** Basic Linux commands

*** ~man~ 
- in most Linux / Unix distributions, this gives you the manual for a function
- format: ~man [command]~
  - just like ~help~ in Windows Command line
*** ~ls~
- listing of files in directory
- Like ~dir~ in Windows command line
*** ~grep~
- macOS / Linux search operator
  - can be complex or simple
*** ~cd~
- Change directory
- Just like in Windows CLI!
*** ~shutdown~
- As it says
- With different operators:
  - i.e. ~shutdown -r~ restarts the machine
*** ~pwd~ vs. ~passwd~
- People get very confused about this, understandably!
  - ~passwd~ changes your password
  - ~pwd~ gives you the "present working directory"
    - Tells you where you are in the filesystem
*** ~mv~
- moves a file, renames a file if it stays in the same directory
*** ~cp~
- copy: source and destination can be specified.  
*** ~rm~
- delete or remove files
*** ~chmod~
- Linux / macOS only (no equivalent in Windows)
- Changes the *mode* of files - permissions
*** ~chown~
- Change ownership of file / directory
*** ~iwconfig/ifconfig~
- Network configuration commands 
  - Like ~ipconfig~ on Windows
  - ~iwconfig~ is the wireless configuration, ~ifconfig~ is the wired configuration (InterFace CONFIGuration)
*** ~ps~
- "Process status" - displays running commands and processes, identifies them by their Process ID (PID)
*** ~su~ / ~sudo~
- Permits a *su* bstitute user to "do" a command
- ~sudo~ user is the "super user" 
  - analogous to "elevated privilege" in Windows
*** ~apt-get~
- In some versions of Linux used to retrieve, install, remove packages
*** ~vi~
- Simple text editor (I prefer ~nano~)
- I make fun of Vi, but it is so tiny and it is always there, no matter what weird little Linux distribution you are in
- So maybe, probably worth learning (but not for the A+!)
