*** ~dd~
- "data duplicator"
  - Used to back up data over network, or to drives, CDs, etc
  - Very powerful, can back up entire (and large) drives
*** ~kill~
- Halts a program or process

* 2.1 – Summarize the importance of physical security measures.

** Mantrap
- Area of controlled access between two secured areas
- Small room with two doors, for example
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.75\textwidth :placement [h] :float nil
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 75%
#+CAPTION: Physical security - mantrap
[[./images2/2-1-mantrap.png]]
** Badge reader
- Access is provided through security badges that contain coded data that identifies users to the security system.
** Smart card
- Smart cards are another way to deliver security tokens to the system. 
- Can both send and receive data, allowing the card and the card reader to verify each other
** Security guard
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.35\textwidth :placement [h] :float nil
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 30%
#+CAPTION: Some kind of guard
[[./images2/2-1-SecurityGurad.png]]
- Can be effective
** Door lock
- Locking doors seem like a simple task, but it can be complicated!
  - Keys can be copied if left unattended
  - Locks can be picked granting unauthorized access
** Biometric locks
 - Using a person’s unique personal attributes such as their Iris, Fingerprint, or Voice to authenticate is known as *biometrics*
** Hardware tokens
- Tokens are a security component necessary for devices to communicate and provide the holder of the token the appropriate access level.
- Card reader, magnetic stripe, etc
** Cable locks
- Cable locks are used to secure valuable items, that can easily be removed from the workplace. 
** Server locks 
- To prevent unauthorized users from opening a server case
** USB locks
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.55\textwidth :placement [h] :float nil
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 70%
#+CAPTION: USB lock
[[./images2/2-1-USBlock.png]]
- These can prevent unauthorized use of a USB port
  - As you may recall, USB ports can be used to boot an outside operating system and can compromise the security of the OS.
** Privacy screen
- Privacy filters are employed by users who work in close proximity to others and require security from "shoulder surfing" 
- Reduces viewing angle of monitor

* 2.2 – Explain logical security concepts.

** Active Directory
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.75\textwidth :placement [h] :float nil
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 80%
#+CAPTION: Active Directory diagram of effective field
[[./images2/2-2-ActiveDirectory.png]]
 - Not really a single service anymore 
   - Now describes broad range of services and related databases for identity-related services
*** Login script
- When a user logs in, a list of commands are executed
  - Batch files, PowerShell scripts, etc that set up the user's identity in the organization's IT infrastructure
  - i.e. access to network shares, servers, email, etc
*** Domain
- The Active Directory organizational hierarchy
  - Often under single internet domain, i.e. Pepsi.com, GMU.edu, Healthcare.gov, etc
  - But can encompass more sites
*** Organizational Units
- *OU* - can contain one or more user groups
  - Allows the simplification of the hierarchy of user roles within the network infrastructure
*** Group Policy/Updates
- Domain resources (workstations, user profiles, privileges,etc
- These are controlled by the group policies of the Organizational Unit
*** Home Folder
- A regular home user (such as yourself) saves files locally to their home folder (i.e. ~C:\Users\[yourname]\Documents~)
  - In an enterprise setup, user's *home folders* can be on a network share, and thus available to the user wherever they go in the organization
*** Folder redirection
- The process in which Active Directory changes the users *home folder* from their workstation to a network share
- This simplifies management and backup requirements
  - Don't have to make a trip out to the user's computer to back up their files

** Software tokens
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.7\textwidth :placement [H]
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 30%
#+CAPTION: Software token on a smartphone
[[./images2/2-2-SoftwareToken.png]]
- Generated security component used for authentication
  - Devices synchronized with server
  - Can be cards, or software on phones / mobile devices
** MDM policies - BYOD vs corporate owned
- Mobile Device Management:
  - Corporate policy that manages personally-owned vs corporate-owned devices
  - Organization may require the installation of security apps in employee's phone under a BYOD (Bring Yoour Own Device) protocol
** Port security
- Used on switches and routers when connected devices communicate with each other over the network
** MAC address filtering
- Using a device's MAC address to permit or deny access
  - Remember this is not foolproof!  MAC addresses can be changed and spoofed
** Certificates
- Digital certificates serve to authorize users and servers
- Valid Certificate Authority is what guarantees encryption in ~https~ protocol and gives you that nice padlock at the top of your browser
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.75\textwidth :placement [h] :float nil
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 0%
#+CAPTION: encryption verification
[[./images2/2-2-httpsLockPepsiDotCom.png]]
** Antivirus/Anti-malware
- Especially in an enterprise context, this kind of security is paramount
  - These programs will examine behavior and content of files against known threats
  - Virus and malware definitions must be updated on a regular basis
  - Best done centrally, like other software updates
** Firewalls - hardware vs software
- Barrier between the dangerous outside network and the LAN / individual computers
- *Hardware firewall* - often found as a part of routers
  - Filters all traffic allowed onto network
  - Hardware firewall only inspects inbound traffic
- *Software firewall* - on individual workstations, usually, such as Windows Defender Firewall
** User authentication/strong passwords
- The first line of security on a network or device
  - Best "strong" passwords made by password generators
    - COMPTIA still recommends those kinds of "strong" passwords with different character types, upper-case, lower-case, etc: ~e5wd#*Ljp2B9G7!y~ for example
    - But, here's a good comic:
#+REVEAL: split
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.99\textwidth :placement [H] :float nil
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 99%
#+CAPTION: An instructive xkcd comic 
[[./images2/2-2-xkcdPasswordStrip.png]]
** Multifactor authentication
- Strong password along with another form of identification / knowledge is superior to a password alone
  - Mantra of multifactor identification:
    - something you know, something you have, something you are, something you do
** Directory permissions
- In both Linux and Windows, permissions and rights can be determined at the levels of individual directories and files
  - Can prevent accidental / unauthorized deletion or modification
  - *NTFS* - Windows file system format
    - very granular levels of permissions, bu not always obvious to user
** VPN
 - *Virtual Private Network* Communicating securely over an insecure pathway
 - Secure, encrypted tunnel between remote users and the private network of a corporation, enterprise, or home
** DLP
- *Data Loss Prevention* - software and hardware mechanisms to check emails going in and out
- It is about data /security/ not backing up data
** Access control lists
- A database of users and devices that are explicitly allowed to access certain networks or devices
- Can be filtered by: users, IP addresses, port numbers
- Some organizations ban entire /regions/ from accessing their network
** Email filtering
- To reduce spam and unwanted emails
- Can scan and block malicious code in emails, phishing, etc
- Often done by your email service, whether it is Google, Microsoft, Yahoo, or even AOL (\sad)
- Organizations will have their own protocols on top of this
** Trusted/untrusted software sources
- From *trusted* purveyors / producers of software
  - These will often be digitally signed
- *Untrusted* from links in spam email, suspicious third-party applications, etc
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.99\textwidth :placement [H]
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 60%
#+CAPTION: totally not a suspicious program.exe
[[./images2/2-2-suspiciousProgram.png]]
** Principle of least privilege
- User's privileges should be kept to the lowest level required to perform their duties
- These minimal privileges can be elevated only when absolutely necessary
  - This is why you go through an extra step to get Administrator / Root privileges even on your home computer
  - In an enterprise context, you *will not* have those privileges and you will have to ask for them
    - (unless your work for the IT department, of course!)

* 2.3 Compare and contrast wireless security protocols and authentication methods.

** Protocols and Encryption
- Any wireless protocol transmits data over the air
  - And it can thus be intercepted
  - The answer is encryption
*** WEP
- Wired Equivalent Privacy
- By 2002, serious flaws had been found in this protocol
  - Key is static and does not change
- [[color:red][_Do not use!!_]]
*** WPA
- Wi-Fi Protected Access
- Temporary successor to WEP
  - Keys constantly changing
  - Used RC4 (or ARC4) simple cipher now shown to be insecure
*** TKIP
- Temporal Key Integrity Protocol
  - Frequently changing 64-bit authentication keys
  - Now shown to be somewhat vulnerable
*** WPA2
- Currently the *best* wireless protection protocol available
  - Uses AES (below) and CCMP (Counter Mode with Cipher Block Chaining Message Authentication Code Protocol)
*** AES
- Advanced Encryption Standard
  - 128-bit key
  - Improves method first used in TKIP
*** Summary
- Best encryption standard is WPA2 with AES

** Authentication
*** Wireless security modes
 - Open - no security
 - WPA2 Personal / WPA2-PSK
   - WPA2 with a Pre-Shared Key
 - WPA2-Enterprise
   - Additional authentication - RADIUS or TACAS (below)
*** Single-factor
- Simplest form of authentication
  - PIN or password
  - Or One Time Passwords (OTP)
*** Multifactor
- Two or more independent authentication methods
*** RADIUS
- Remote Access Dial-in User Service
  - Centralized authentication
  - Every user has their own identity and password
  - No password to share
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.75\textwidth :placement [h] :float nil
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 95%
#+CAPTION: RADIUS authentication
[[./images2/2-3-RADIUS.png]]
*** TACACS
- Terminal Access Controller Access-Control System
  - Remote authentication protocol
  - Newer version is TACACS+

* 2.4 Given a scenario, detect, remove, and prevent malware using appropriate tools and methods.

** Malware
- Portmanteau of "malicious software"
  - Any software designed to cause damage to a computer, server, or network
*** Ransomware
- Malefactors damage your computer / network and promise to undo the damage for money
  - Often network drives will be encrypted by the malware, and after payment the encryption key will be given
*** WannaCry 2017
 - Global ransomware attack, hit the UK NHS particularly hard
   - [[https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2017/may/12/nhs-ransomware-cyber-attack-what-is-wanacrypt0r-20][Link to Guardian story]]
   - Many hospitals / clinics in the UK were still running Windows XP and unpatched Windows 7 machines
   - You don't need to know about this for the A+ but it's a good story!
*** Trojan
- Infected versions of legitimate-looking software
  - Some can disable antivirus, System Restore
*** Keylogger 
- Program sneaks in to monitor and send out your keystrokes
  - Passwords, credit card numbers, everything you type
  - Sends it out in the clear, circumvents encryption
  - often part of trojans
*** Rootkit
  - Name comes from Unix superuser - root
  - Modifies core system files (kernel)
  - Dastardly and invisible
  - Works as root, has complete control
    - Only defense is prevention - once infected, it is too late!
*** Virus
- Infect the system and replicate themselves
  - Usually transmitted through executable files
  - Can be harmless or extremely damaging
  - Importance of regular security updates
  - Can lead to telling slowness of computer, increased network activity
*** Botnet
- Groups of computers / devices taken over by viruses / trojans
  - Then used to infect more machines, run DDOS attacks, or do whatever
*** Worm
- Self-replicating malicious software
  - unlike viruses, need no human interaction to spread
    - Uses networks as medium of transmission
    - Often worse and harder to control than viruses
*** Spyware
- Malware designed to spy on you in various ways
  - Monitors your activity, sends the information back
  - Can include keylogging

** Tools and methods

*** Antivirus
- Keep it updated and running
*** Anti-malware
- Can work together with antivirus
- [[https://www.malwarebytes.com/][Malwarebytes]] probably the best known
*** Recovery console
- In Windows 10, Recovery Environment (RE) replaced the recovery console
  - Powerful and dangerous, a last resort
  - Can repair many things including the Master Boot Record (MBR)

#+reveal: split
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.75\textwidth :placement [h] :float nil
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 90%
#+CAPTION: Windows Recovery Environment
[[./images2/2-4-RecoveryEnvironment.png]]
*** Backup/restore
- Service first became available with Windows 7
  - Still in Windows 8.1 and 10
*** End user education
- Often the most important part of prevention
  - Don't click on things!
  - Don't open that weird email!
  - Oh, but they just keep on doing it. 
*** Secure DNS
- Offered by external services, but can also set up yourself
  - Cloudflare, for example
  - Can block harmful websites based on lists
  - [[https://pi-hole.net/][Pi-hole]] is a good example of a selfhosted type (will not be on exam!)

* 2.5 Compare and contrast social engineering, threats, and vulnerabilities.

** Social Engineering
- Can be difficult to predict and protect against
- Changing and adapting methods
  - All human weaknesses can be exploited
  - Gaining inappropriate levels of trust
*** Some common angles
 - Urgency
 - Appearance of legitimacy
   - We make easy assumptions - uniforms, ID cards
 - Intimidation
 - Scarcity
 - False familiarity
*** Phishing
- Usually delivered by email or messaging system
  - Usually with malicious link
  - Could be Facebook, Instagram, etc
  - Message contains a malicious link
  - At first glance will look legitimate
*** Spear phishing
 - Phishing with inside information
 - Use of familiar emails, formats
 - Spear phishing the CEO called "whaling"
   - Again, false legitimacy 
*** Dumpster diving
- Going through the garbage
- Usually not illegal to do
- Importance of data destruction
  - Shredding, destroying media
*** Impersonation
 - Appeals to authority
 - The more keys you have, the more authoritative you appear
*** Shoulder surfing
 - Insecure access to screen by others
   - Mobility makes us more vulnerable
   - We might not be aware we are targets
*** Tailgating
 - Using others to gain access to restricted areas
 - Most security is at the borders
** DDoS
 - Distributed Denial of Service
 - An army of computers mobilized to overwhelm a service
 - Large botnets can be millions of computers
** Mitigation of DDOS
- Identifying patterns
- High grade firewall
- ISP may have mitigation strategies
- Again, Cloudflare has made this their business
** Zero-day
- An exploitation of an OS / application weakness that has not previously been reported
** Man-in-the-middle
 - Uses a webserver in-between user and destination
 - Redirects traffic
 - VPN makes you more secure
#+ATTR_LATEX: :width 0.75\textwidth :placement [h] :float nil
#+ATTR_HTML: :width 80%
#+CAPTION: Man in the Middle attack
[[./images2/2-5-ManInTheMiddle.png]]
** Brute force
- Guessing passwords over and over
- Sometimes sophisticated methods, sometimes not
** Dictionary
- Checking all words in dictionary one-by-one
** Rainbow table
 - Pre-built series of hashes
 - Calculations have been done for you already
 - "Salted" hashes less vulnerable to this
   - additional values added to hash
** Spoofing
 - Pretending to be something you are not
 - Can spoof emails, MAC addresses, phone numbers
** Non-compliant systems
- Systems that are not regularly updated or patched,
* 3.1 – Given a scenario, use the best practice methodology to resolve problems.

** Always consider corporate policies, procedures, and impacts before implementing changes
** 1. Identify the problem
- Question the user and identify user changes to computer and perform backups before making
 changes
- Inquire regarding environmental or infrastructure changes 
- Review system and application logs

** 2. Establish a theory of probable cause (question the obvious)

 - If necessary, conduct external or internal research based on symptoms

** 3. Test the theory to determine cause

- Once the theory is confirmed, determine the next steps to resolve problem
- If theory is not confirmed, establish new theory or escalate

** 4. Establish a plan of action to resolve the problem and implement the solution
- Build the plan
  - Calculate and document impact of solution
  - Backup / backout if things go bad
- Fix it!
** 5. Verify full system functionality and, if applicable, implement preventive measures
- Restart the machine
- Confirm the fix
- Discuss with user
** 6. Document findings, actions, and outcomes
- Contribute to knowledge base
- Useful if problem occurs again
- In a legal sense, didn't happen until you document it
